PROTECTED STRUCTURE-Planning permission for development at this site at No. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper, and No. 31-33 Henry Street, Dublin 1. The site is bounded by Henry Street to the south, O'Connell Street Upper to the east, Henry Place to the west and No. 67 O'Connell Street Upper to the north. The site area is 0.030 ha. No. 68 O'Connell Street Upper is a protected structure. The development will consist of the demolition of no. 32 and 33 Henry Street and the partial demolition and alteration of the interior of no. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street to facilitate the integration of these buildings. The development will consist of the restoration and refurbishment of the existing upper floor facades of No. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street. The roof profile of No. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street will be preserved and refurbished. The existing shop fronts on No. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street will be replaced with a new shop front. Existing blocked up windows located on the rear of No. 68 O'Connell Street Upper will be reinstated. The existing lightwell located to the rear of No. 68 O'Connell Street Upper will be retained and will be covered by a glass roof at third floor level. A three storey over basement retail unit will be construction in place of No. 32 and 33 Henry Street (Block B) and this unit will be integrated with No. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street (Block A) to create one retail unit which will be part three storey and part four storey over basement. This unit will have a new shopfront which will integrate with the replacement shopfront on No. 68,69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street. The total gross floor area of the proposed development is 1,207sqm of which 560sqm is retained floorspace in No. 68, 69 O'Connell Street Upper and No. 31 Henry Street (Block A) and 647sqm is new floorspace (Block B). The gross floor area of the buildings to be demolished is 661.2sqm. The overall development will comprise 981sqm gross floor area of retail floorspace located at basement, ground, first and second floor level and 226sqm gross floor area of ancillary floorspace including office, storage, plant and staff facilities located at third floor level. A proposed lantern will extend from third floor level in Block B to 4 metres above roof level. The building has a maximum height of 18.9 metres above street level. There will be access to a roof deck area for maintenance purposes only. The retail unit will be accessed from O'Connell Street Upper, Henry Street and Henry Place. The floor levels of the existing basements which partially extend under Henry Street, O'Connell Street Upper and Henry Place will be lowered by 1-1.5 metres. Pavement lights will be placed at street level on Henry Street and Henry Place. The proposal includes the provision of all internal arrangements including lift and stair cores, disabled access arrangements and all site development and ancillary works.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE-Application for planning permission at no. 3, 4, 5, 6. Parnell Street, Dublin 1. No. 3 is a protected structure, and the site is in an Architectural Conservation Area. The development will consist/consists of: No. 3 Parnell Street is three storey over basement and is a protected structure. The first and second floor are residential and the ground floor is retail. There were associated stores in the basement. No. 3 is in poor structural condition. There has been a recent dangerous building notice issued on the property to make it safe. No. 4, 5 and 6 were originally three storey over basement. There was commercial use on the ground floor. There were associated stores in the basement. The first and second floor were residential. No. 6 is a single storey commercial unit on the ground floor only. Due to the dangerous structural condition of no. 4 and no. 5 they have been demolished to ground floor level by order of Dublin City Council Dangerous Building Section. All original brick and slate have been retained on site at no. 6 to allow for the conservation of no. 3. There is an historic fireplace on the ground and basement floor of no. 4 which is to be conserved and restored. The chimney breast on the first, second and third floor of no. 4 is to be retained. The development will consist of demolition of remaining ground floor front and rear facade of no. 4, 5, and 6 to allow for the construction of a new boutique hotel at no. 4, 5 and 6 and the conservation of no. 3 as part of the new proposed hotel. The proposed boutique hotel will be 5 storeys over basement. The hotel will be entered through a centrally foyer at no. 5 at ground level of no. 6, it is proposed to have a restaurant that fronts both Parnell Street and Jervis Lane. At first, second and third floor of no. 4, 5, and no. 6 there are 18 double bedrooms (6 at 17sqm 6 at 15sqm and 3 at 19.5sqm and 3 at 18.5sqm) on the recessed fourth floor of no. 4, 5, 6, it is proposed to have three meeting rooms (1 at 38.5sqm, 1 at 36.3sqm, 1 at 23sqm). It is proposed to have stores in the existing basement of no. 4 and toilets in the new basement of no. 6. To the rear of no. 3, 4 and 5 it is proposed to conserve the boundary garden walls of calp stone, brick and beach stone and to form a new garden at ground level with granite and salvaged brick paving with planter to rear. (no. 3 will be separate) On Parnell Street the proposed new hotel entrance at No. 5 is copper. The proposed shop front at the restaurant of no. 6 is aluminium. The proposed hotel pub front at no. 4 is hardwood. The proposed new shop front at no. 3 is painted hardwood. On Jervis Lane the proposed shop front at the restaurant at no. 6 is aluminium. The entrance door is copper to accentuate the side entrance. The kitchen facade is painted timber. The proposed new facades on the first, second and third floor is red brick. The proposed windows are double glazed hardwood timber with copper window guards. The conservation of no. 3 Parnell which is the protected structure to allow for the renovation of the shop on the ground floor and a hotel apartment comprising of two bedrooms on the second floor and a kitchen and living room on the first floor with new three storey bathroom block to rear. The proposed work at no. 3 consists of the careful removal and retention of the blue Bangor slates to allow for the reinstatement of slates to the roof. Essential repair and repointing of the front facade. Essential repair to the rear facade comprising of the careful removal of courses of brick to beneath the window on the half landing to allow for reinstatement of same with the re-salvaged brick from no. 4 and no. 5. Essential repairs to floors. Opening up of floors to allow for the splicing and repair and new joists where necessary. Essential conservation works to interior walls. The conservation of cornices and reinstatement of cornices where missing. The reinstatement of plaster ceilings with 1hour fire rated ceilings. Allow for conservation of windows or new windows to matching detail where required. Allow for the removal of the windows on the half landing to allow for the construction of a bathroom block to the rear with flat roof below existing roof level with new buff yellow brick to define new structure. Careful removal of the temporary beams and ties that are installed to secure the safety of the building. New separate drainage to rear of no. 3, 4, 5 and 6. Total site area is 300sqm. The proposed area of no. 3 and existing basement of no. 4 and no. 5 is 1264sqm.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE - The development will consist of demolition, refurbishment, modification and extension to the existing Historic Buildings (Dargan, Milltown & Beit Wing) and Millennium Wing of NGI complex, ancillary areas and services and comprise the carrying out of works to Protected Structures. 

This application seeks permission for the following interventions:

Merrion Square Entrance Area (protected structure): removal of the steps, ramp and railing at the main entrance, modification of the level at the entrance and repair works to the existing portico. Modification of the existing roof structure above the entrance to reinstate the original design. Removal and modification of the existing walls and finishes in the ground floor lobby to allow for new configuration of the entrance. Removal of the existing late 20th century ceiling in the entrance lobby to reinstate the original design. Removal of the toilet and existing partitions on the mezzanine level above the entrance lobby. Reinstatement of 3no. original internal window openings to the entrance hall below. Removal of the existing steps and lift hoist and modification of the existing window opening in the first floor lobby to allow for access to the lift landing. Forming a new door opening in the lobby. Removal of the existing 20th century security lobby to the stair on second floor. Removal of a section of the slab, structural wall and partition to form a new stair access to Beit Wing. Removal of the existing stair access to attic space to allow for new steps. Provision of new partition arrangement on the second floor and in the attic space. Reconfiguration of the toilet layout on the lower ground floor. Removal and modifications to the structural walls in the lobby area to allow for new door arrangement. 

Interventions to the Dargan Wing (protected structure) as follows: Repair works to the existing facades. Removal of 7no. late 20th century window panels to replace with stone matching the existing facade finish. Reinstatement of 5no. window openings to the former external Courtyard on ground floor and mezzanine level. Replacement of the existing late 20th century partition walls in the west gallery on ground floor level. Creation of new door opening in the north wall from ground floor west gallery. Modification of the 2no. door openings on mezzanine & first floor. Removal of existing ground bearing slab and forming trench under the floor of lower ground floor to facilitate access of services from energy centre. Removal of existing partitions, ceilings and wall finishes and reconfiguration of the layout on lower ground floor to accommodate security, staff facilities and office areas. 

Intervention to the external courtyard running east/west between the Dargan and Milltown Wings (protected structure) as follows: Removal of existing workshop structure. Removal of the existing 3no. lift cores, fire stairs and adjacent service areas to allow for new vertical & horizontal circulation and services distribution. Provision of ground bearing floor slab at lower ground floor level to accommodate staff areas, and new supporting structure of Sculpture Court at ground floor level. Provision of secondary glazing to all existing window openings. Provision of new glass roof structure spanning between Dargan and Milltown Wings. Provision of the new plant areas on the roof level at the west and east side of new atrium. 

Interventions to the Milltown Wing (protected structure) as follows: Removal of the existing roof light and roof covering from the roof to facilitate new plant room. Repair works to the existing facades. Creation of 3no. openings in the external west facade to facilitate connection to the fire escape stair. Reinstatement of 4no. window openings to the former external Courtyard on ground floor. Forming of 2no. door openings in south wall to ground and first floor galleries. Removal of radiators & radiator cases from the galleries. Replacement of steps and lift hoist to Beit Wing first floor. Breaking-out and reinstatement of slab to accommodate service trenches below lower ground floor level. Removal of the existing plant room from lower ground floor level. Reconfiguration of the painting storage and former staff areas at lower ground floor level including new door openings to accommodate Reheat Kitchen, and new Painting Storage. 

Interventions to the Beit Wing (protected structure) as follows: removal of the existing coat room on ground floor level and reconfiguration of the area to facilitate new entrance arrangement. Removal of the existing stair to Milltown Wing and toilet on lower ground floor level to facilitate new steps & toilet. Provision of new locker room on lower ground floor level. 

General works to the Historic Buildings (protected structure) as follows: Upgrading of the internal fabric to achieve required fire rating. Replacement of the existing services. General refurbishment of internal fixtures and finishes. Provision of new lighting, security, fire detection and suppression systems. Provision of new information and fire escape signage. 

Interventions to the Millennium Wing as follows: Forming new opening in the external facade facing Dessie's Lane. New plants on the top of the roof to serve Historic Wings. 

New Energy Centre below the Forecourt at the Merrion Square entrance as follows: Provision of structure extending 1 storey below ground to accommodate Chiller, Boiler, CHP, LV, HV and Pump rooms, water storage tanks, and corridor connecting to existing underground tunnel linking NGI complex with no. 88 Merrion Square. 

New Fire Escape Stair and Bridge Connection in Dessie's Lane as follows: Provision of new stair core and bridging link corridor to Millennium Wing with associated supporting structure. 

The proposed development will increase the existing floor space from c.16,540sqm to c. 17,970sqm. 

Permission is also sought for all associated site development, landscaping and boundary treatment works & to include relocation and renovation of (protected structure) William Dargan Statue and rising the external ground level at the Merrion Square entrance by c.450mm.

Permission is sought to vary a condition attaching to earlier permissions to develop an extension, including conference rooms. The condition stated ''The proposed conference rooms and meeting rooms shall be for the stated purpose only. They shall not be used as function rooms where music is played or as dancehalls or discotheques, except with a prior grant of permission''. This condition was Condition 3 in the original permission for the extension (Reg Ref 2328/99) granted by An Bord Pleanala (PL29N.117196) in 2000 and Condition 2 of the application to vary the original permission (Reg Ref 4083/06) granted by An Bord Pleanala (PL29N.220345) in 2007. Permission is sought in this application to vary this condition and replace it by a new condition which controls the use of the conference rooms. This new condition shall specify that in relation to events in the Hotel the resultant Leq from music entertainment noise should not exceed the representative background noise level L90 (without entertainment noise) by more than 5dB in the 63Hz and 12Hz octave bands when measured in the vicinity of noise sensitive locations.

Development at a site formerly known as the 'Irish Distillers Building', Smithfield, Dublin 7.  The site is bounded by Phoenix Street to the south, Smithfield Square to the west, new church street to the north, and Bow Street to the east.  The site includes the surface car park adjacent to the Irish Distillers Building.  The development will consist of: The demolition of all existing structures on site including the 'Irish Distillers Building'; the construction of a mixed use commercial development (predominantly office with an element of retail / cafe use) of seven storeys above ground level, with three levels below ground level, with a gross floor area (gfa) of 25,415sqm.  The proposed development provides 16,592sqm of office space distributed from ground floor to sixth floor level; 1,267sqm of retail / cafe (total of 4 no. units located along Phoenix Street and Smithfield Square at ground floor level with unit no. 2 split over ground floor and first floor levels); provision of a ground floor level corner terrace fronting onto Phoenix Street and Smithfield Square associated with corner retail / cafe use (Unit2); provision of terraces associated with office use are provided at Fifth and Sixth floor levels on north, east, south and west elevations.  The main office pedestrian entrance & reception areas are proposed at ground floor level from Smithfield Square, Phoenix Street and Bow Street.  A central atrium links the main service cores and reception areas.  A separate entrance to ground level office space is provided at Ground Floor level from New Church Street.  The entrances to the retail / cafe units are proposed at ground floor level from Smithfield Square and Phoenix Street.  A double basement is proposed to provide 98 no. car parking spaces, and ancillary facilities (plant / storage, refuse stores, etc).  The lower Ground floor level (also located below ground level) will provide 214no. cycle spaces, shower and changing facilities ad 1,124sqm of archive / storage area.  vehicular access to the development is from Bow Street, via a two-way ramp down to basement levels, located in the east part of the site. PERMISSION & RETENTION - Development at a site of 0.6087ha. The development will increase part of the Eccles Street
(south) elevation of the hospital by one-storey to provide six storeys to correspond with the height of the existing west wing, plus extensions to existing floors resulting in an increase to part of the Eccles Place (north) elevation by one to three storeys to
provide a maximum of five storeys plus rooftop plant. The overall gross floor area will increase from 18,433 square metres to 21,786 square metres, the development will comprise alterations and extensions to the Mater Private Hospital, comprising:
the construction of an extension (28.4 square metres) to the Central Sterile Services Department (CSSD) within circulation space associated with the eastern car park at Level 00; the replacement of three number car parking spaces in the eastern car park
at Level 00 with open plant areas and an additional 26 number staff bicycle parking spaces; the construction of a catering staff changing room (75.65 square metres) and two number stores (25 square metres and 28 square metres respectively) within the
former western car park at Level 00; the installation of two number surface water attenuation tanks (41 cubic metres in total) at Levels 00 and 01 respectively; the infill of an internal courtyard area at Level 01 to provide an administration area (61.2 square metres) for the diagnostic imaging centre; the enclosure of an existing external plant area (117 square metres) at the north-west corner of the hospital at Level 01; the provision of six number public bicycle parking spaces at Level 01 accessed from Eccles Street; the infill of an internal lightwell area at Level 02 to provide additional floor area (42.6 square metres) for facilities associated with an operating theatre; the construction of an extension at the north-west corner of the hospital (facing Leo Street
and Eccles Place) at Levels 02, 03 and 04, to provide additional theatre, ward and services facilities (681square metres at Level 02, 347 square metres at Level 03 and 343 square metres at Level 04 respectively) [set back enclosed plant rooms will be
positioned on the roofs of the proposed extension at Levels 03 (121 square metres) and 05 (101 square metres) respectively]; the enclosure of an existing external plant area (22 square metres) at the south-east corner of the hospital at Level 04; the
construction of a single-storey extension (1,299 square metres) above existing roof level at Level 05 to the main hospital block, fronting Eccles Street, for additional inpatient and out-patient accommodation, plant areas and services; the construction of
an extension (43 square metres) to the eye laser department at Level 05 on the west wing of the hospital; the installation of an external pipe gantry at Level 05 to distribute chilled water to air handling units; and the installation of a low-level metal
screen, mechanical extract fans, a metal guardrail, and a solar panel array (26.9 square metres), all at Level 06. The development will also comprise: the demolition of an existing security hut on Eccles Place in order to provide a new pedestrian entrance
and gate; the provision of a central atrium in the existing lightwell to improve the quality of the main reception; extensions and modifications to the existing front (south) elevation, surrounding the hospital entrance on Eccles Street, comprising the
replacement of the existing stepped glazed element with a glazed conservatory [including extensions at Level 03 (13.2 square metres) and Level 04 (4.5 square metres) respectively], the installation of an entrance canopy at Level 02, the addition
of a smoking shelter, the relocation of an external stair that provides access from Level 00 to Level 01, new signage and all associated site works above and below ground. The development for which RETENTION permission is sought comprises:
the change of use of the former western car park (227 square metres) at Level 00 for ancillary hospital uses (including waste management, storage and bicycle parking); the construction of seven number storage/workshop rooms (92.3 square metres in
total) in the former western car park at Level 00; the replacement of two number car parking spaces in the eastern car park at Level 00 with two number open plant areas (gas plant and reverse osmosis water plant respectively); and the installation of three
number modular structures (53.8 square metres in total) in the eastern yard (to the rear of numbers 110-112 Dorset Street) at Level 00, providing additional hospital storage facilities.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE - The development will consist of the provision of a new pedestrian access gate between the National Botanic Gardens and Prospect (Glasnevin) Cemetery.  The gate is located along the existing protected boundary railing adjacent to the existing protected Dog Tower.  The development will involve the removal of a 4m section of the existing protected railing, provision of a new security controlled access gate, paved steps, and a paved gently sloped access route designed for universal access.  The works will also involve the regrading and resurfacing of the existing approach path to the proposed new gate (within the cemetery).  in addition the development will require associated lighting, landscaping and civil works.  The proposed development is within the curtilage of the National Botanic Gardens, which is a conservation area and contains the following protected structures: The Curvilinear Range, The Palm House Complex, The Cactus / Lily House and the Dog Tower.  The proposed development is also within the curtilage of Prospect (Glasnevin) Cemetery which contains the following  protected structures: O'Connell Monument, Mortuary Chapel, former Superintendents Lodge, all perimeter stone walls and watch towers, plinth walls and railings, entrance piers and gates including pedestrian gates.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: For development on part of the Guinness Brewery lands to the north of James's Street, Dublin 8 (The subject site contains two Protected Structures - granite piers and the Guinness Building on Victoria Quay known as Victoria Quay House). The subject site is bound by Victoria Quay to the north and Watling Street to the east, and existing brewery areas to the south and west. The proposed development comprises of the construction of a new brewhouse and a consolidation of existing brewery uses, including the relocation of existing Brewhouse functions from Guinness Brewery lands to the south of James's Street. The proposed development will have a combined overall floor area of approx 12,008sq.m. The development includes the demolition of six existing structures with a combined floor area of 3,124 approx sq.m. These buildings include a disused fire damaged Lager Plant (1389 sq.m) Mechanical Maintenance Workshop (610 sq.m), Electrical Maintenance Workshop (275 sq.m), Fork Lift Maintenance Workshop (180 sq.m) Staff Facilitates Building (245 sq.m), and a disused Utilities Pumphouse (425 sq.m).

The development comprises:
The provision of a new relocated upgraded Brewhouse Building will increase the annual output capacity of the brewery to 8.2 million hl (hectolitre) and with an overall floor area of approx 9,314 sq.m. The output capacity of the existing brewery is approx 5.0 million hl. This building will generally be of two stories with a height of approximately 14.1M (18.3M OD), with an associated grain intake facility and silo structure with a height of approximately 25.1M (29.3M OD) on the east face of the building, together with a flue stack with a height of approx 28.1M (32.34MOD), and a series of tank structures containing 23 tanks with a maximum height of approximately 25.8M (30.0MOD) on the west face of the building. The dimensions of the proposed building are approx. 113M x 90M.

An extension of approx 2,087 sq.m to the existing Fermentation and Beer Processing Plant. This extension will be located on the western side of the existing Plant Building, and will continue the form of the existing building, with a single storey podium supporting a series of fermentation tank structures, with a maximum height of approx. 19.15M (24.6MOD). 

The provision at the existing Central Utilities Area of a new incoming Water Treatment Plantroom, with a floor area of approx 280 sq.m, two associated external storage tanks, and associated plant. The Plantroom height will be approx 7.0M (13.26MOD) and the maximum tank height will be approx 9.0M (15.26M OD).

Increasing the capacity of the existing Waste Water Treatment plant by the addition of two new treatment tanks, with a maximum height of approx 8.1M (11.3 MOD), and associated plant. This will include the provision of a screening building enclosure on the Walting Street frontage, with a floor area of 327dq.m, and a height of roof ridge level of approximately 9.8M (13.0MOD). 

There are no car parking spaces proposed as part of this development. A new internal one way road network will be provided within the site. Vehicular access to the proposed development will be via the existing brewery access on Victoria Quay. Two temporary construction vehicular access points are proposed at existing gateways on Victoria Quay.

It is proposed to upgrade the existing Victoria Quay boundary wall from its starting point adjacent to the corner with Walting Street as far as the existing vehicular access gateway to the brewery, to incorporate 32no. feature lights mounted on the existing piers. These works will include facade upgrading of the Guinness Building on Victoria Quay, and restoration works to the gateway piers, both of which are Protected Structures. The works include insertion of two new sets of non functioning gates into two number existing gateways. The proposed gates will include the harp symbol and the Guinness logo. Works to the wall will include provision of viewing slots through the wall towards the new Brewhouse at strategic locations. It is also proposed to insert 12 no. viewing slots approx. 450mm wide in the Victoria Quay boundary wall. 

The Brewhouse grain intake tower structure will incorporate externally illuminated Guinness Harp logo signage at a high level on all sides. The north facade of the Brewhouse facing Victoria Quay includes a glazed gallery which will incorporate an internally illuminated Guinness logo sign. The south facade of the Brewhouse will include externally illuminated Guinness logo and harp symbol signage.

The proposed development includes all associated site development works, internal site  lighting and landscaping. All of the above is proposed on a site of approx. 26,960 sq.m (2.7 hectares). 

An Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) has been prepared in respect of this planning application. The application relates to development which is for the purposes of an activity requiring an Integrated Pollution Prevention Control (IPPC) Licence.

The total floorspace of buildings to be demolished comprises approx. 7,890 square metres (sq.m). It is proposed to construct a new mixed use building, part twenty two storeys (with a height of approx. 93.65 m from footpath level (96.85 m OD) a parapet screen level) and part three storeys (with a height of approx. 17.15 m from footpath level (20.35 m OD) to parapet level) with mezzanine at ground leveel, all over two basement levels, together with plant room of approx. 3.4 m height at roof level, behind a parapet screen of approx. 3 m in height. The proposed development has an overall appearance equivalent to a part twenty three storey and part four storey building. The skylift shaft extends 7 m in height above the parapet screen level. The building from footpath level is approx. 93.65 m (96.85 m OD) to parapet screen level, approx 94.5 m (97.25 m OD) to the top plant room and 100.65m (103.85 m OD) to the top of the Skylight shaft. The total height of the proposed building from footpath level is approx. 100.65 m (103.85 m OD). The new building will accommodate offices (approx. 9,822.9 sq.m) at levels 1 to 17; public heritage centre including Skydeck viewing facility and cafe (approx. 1,787.8 sq.m) at levels 18 to 21; shared access, reception areas, coffee shop and associated uses at ground floor level (approx. 864 sq.m) with visitor ticketing area, toilets, Skylight lobby and related services areas including plant at ground floor mezzaanine (approx. 492 sq.m); theatre/conference area and auditorium with pre-conference circulation space, ancillary accommodation for theatre and auditorium, associated facilities, including toilets etc. (approx. 1014 sq.m) at level -1 associated servicing, plant and ancillary areas, including staff showers, associated changing areas and locker facilities at level -2; provision of 74 no. cycle parking spaces (double stacked) at ground floor level, accessed via a ramp off Old Abbey Street and 24 no. on. street cycle parking spaces on Beresford Place adjacemt to the eastern side of the building; all associated servicing, staff, circulation aand ancillary spaces throughout the building. The total gross floor area of the proposed building is approx. 14,688.4 sq.m with external landscaped terraces at level 1 (approx. 121 sq.m) and level 3 (approx. 33.5 sq.m) and double height winter gardens at levels 5 and 11 on the east facade and level 9 on the west facade; associated plant at roof level (approx. 62.7 sq.m), at ground floor mezzanine level (approx, 115 sq.m) and at basement level -2 )approx. 641 sq.m); provision of ESB substation (approx. 16sqm) and LV switch room (approx. 28 sq.m) accessed from a raised platform set back from Old Abbey Street. All associated site development, services and related works; provision of landscaping at site frontage at Eden Quay, including new steps and disabled ramp access to new building entrance. All on a site of some 0.127 hectares. Existing vehicular access to ground floor car park off Old Abbey Street to be removed. Existing off-street parking provision at ground level (19 no. car spaces) to be removed. There is no vehicular access proposed to the building and no on-site car parking provision. Servicing/deliveries as per existing loading bay on Beresford Place and along Old Abbey Street. Servicing/rear pedestrian access off Old Abbey Street, public entrance (pedestrian) to building off Eden Quay. An Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) has been prepared in respect of this planning application and will be submitted to Dublin City Counil with this application.
